Rearrangement of the Middle East
President Bush, the Palestinian prime minister Mazen, and Israeli prime minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about concluding a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into the American Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the planning staff at the US Department of State, explains his "roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What has been achieved in Iraq - and what in particular the Iraqi people can now achieve with the help of the Americans - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented and peaceful Iraq could bring about reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
However, it will take some time before far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the entire Middle East take effect.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security, economic, and political aspects.
Thanks to the advance planning by the Americans and the rest of the world and thanks to the rapid, concentrated and targeted intervention by the coalition forces during the war, the humanitarian challenge is less than anticipated.
Here and there there is a need for humanitarian aid, but the announced massive crisis fortunately has never occurred.
There are relatively few refugees and internally displaced persons within Iraq. In most cases, the supply of food, water and medicines is sufficient or at least improving.
The American government has made approximately 600 million dollars available for immediate humanitarian aid through the UN and non-governmental organizations.
In addition, we must restore basic order in Iraq.
Security is an indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without security, people cannot rebuild their country, cannot return to work or to schools.
After Saddam's fall, there was a wave of looting, lawlessness, and settling of scores.
Now it is the top priority to bring an end to this violence.
Furthermore, it must be the task of international troops to ensure and eliminate all weapons of mass destruction, prevent the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts, and ensure that none of Iraq's neighbors further worsen the already fragile situation.
In the long term, we must help the Iraqis to rebuild their police and military structures, so that they can ensure their own security without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be viewed more accurately as economic renewal.
Physical capital is in better condition than expected and the modern Iraq possesses a large reservoir of human capital.
In contrast to many other post-war scenarios, there are plenty of raw materials to process in Iraq.
The USA provide more than 2 billion dollars to support the first reconstruction efforts.
Oil production will be raised to a better level.
Among the long-term challenges are increasing oil production and reducing Iraq's enormous debts.
The decision by the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very commendable.
Given the many religious, ethnic, geographic, and political rifts in Iraqi society, helping with the political renewal of Iraq is undoubtedly the most difficult task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The goal of the Americans - an intact Iraq where the law is respected and the government comes about democratically - is not a castle in the air, especially not because Iraq has an educated population and a fairly large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue on the course it has set and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported so that the enormous political potential for constructive decisions can be utilized.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have effects on the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is hardly any foreign policy topic that occupies and polarizes public opinion more strongly than the Palestinian issue.
Almost a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratic Palestinian state in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU and the United Nations, the USA developed a plan that brings us step by step closer to this goal.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent a significant step in this direction.
Now, Palestinians and Israelis must be brought to set this process in motion and take measures to improve the situation, in order to subsequently tackle broader issues at the negotiation table.
Finally, it cannot be acceptable that terrorists render the peace process futile forever.
However, a solution to the Palestinian issue is not automatically also a solution to all the problems of the Middle East.
Clearly and unequivocally are the challenges that Iran poses to us. This country is developing weapons of mass destruction and supported terrorism.
Such behavior mocks the norms and rules of the international community and isolates Iran and its people.
If Iran continues like this, it will have consequences.
However, if Iran turns away from terrorism and the construction of catastrophic weapons, the USA is ready to reestablish good relations with this country.
Just as the USA is ready to approach Syria when substantial changes in stance are made there.
A more general question is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
America has tolerated too long the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as the governments were friendly and supported regional stability, outsiders had no reason to advocate for a representative form of government.
We have painfully come to realize that closed political systems lead to resentment and extremism against the interests of the USA, the West, and the whole world.
Therefore, we support democracy and political reforms through the Partnership Initiative for the Middle East launched in December 2002 by Secretary of State Colin Powell.
Closed economic systems also pose a danger.
As the previous year's "Arab Human Development Report" (Report on the Development Status of Arab Countries) shows, Arab countries of the Middle East have remained far behind other regions in the areas of personal freedom, women's rights, as well as economic and social development.
For too long these countries have had to watch as the economic upswing passed them by.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
If his recently expressed proposal for a free trade zone between the USA and the Middle East were realized within a decade, that would be a solid basis for such development.
